Here's a JavaScript function that takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is a valid prime number. If it finds a prime number, it prints the number to the console:
```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) {
    return false;
  }
  for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
    if (num % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}

function checkForPrimes(arr) {
  if (arr.length !== 5) {
    console.error("Input array must have exactly 5 numbers.");
    return;
  }

  for (const num of arr) {
    if (isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(`The number ${num} is a prime number.`);
    }
  }
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [2, 5, 8, 11, 15];
checkForPrimes(numbers);
```
The `isPrime` function checks if a given number is a prime number, and the `checkForPrimes` function iterates through the input array and calls the `isPrime` function to check each number. If a prime number is found, it prints the number to the console.

